# A Two-Sided EntropyŌĆōError Sandwich for Finite Partitions

**Anonymous** ┬Ę Anonymous Institution

---

## Abstract

For a finite partition $\Pi$ of a finite set $V$ and a binary label
$f : V \to \{0,1\}$, let $\varepsilon^{*}_{\Pi}$ denote the minimum
error of any predictor that is constant on each cell of $\Pi$, and
let $H(f \mid \Pi)$ denote the partition-conditional Shannon entropy
of $f$ (in bits, under uniform vertex weighting). We give the
two-sided closed-form bracket

$$
H_{\mathrm{bin}}^{-1}\!\bigl(H(f \mid \Pi)\bigr)
\;\le\; \varepsilon^{*}_{\Pi}
\;\le\; \tfrac{1}{2}\,H(f \mid \Pi),
$$

where $H_{\mathrm{bin}}^{-1} : [0,1] \to [0,1/2]$ is the inverse
binary entropy on its increasing branch. The two inequalities are
respectively the Fano (1961) and HellmanŌĆōRaviv (1970) bounds
specialised to the partition channel, packaged in the
FederŌĆōMerhav (1994) achievable-region form. We give one short
proof that derives both halves as the optimal values of opposite
Jaynes maximum-entropy programs on the cell statistics, making
explicit a primal/dual duality between the FederŌĆōMerhav
concave-envelope construction and the Massey-style Lagrangian
calculation. We prove that the upper coefficient $1/2$ is
unimprovable by any uniform constant and that the lower
$H_{\mathrm{bin}}^{-1}$ cannot be replaced by any pointwise-larger
continuous function. Tightness witnesses are constructed
explicitly on both boundaries of the achievable region. All proofs
are elementary, use no measure-theoretic axioms beyond finite
sums, and are amenable to mechanisation in proof assistants.

---

## 1. Introduction

A classical question in information theory and statistical pattern
recognition is how tightly the Shannon entropy of a label given a
discrete side observation controls the error of the best predictor
based on that observation. For a binary label $f$ observed through
a finite-alphabet channel $\Pi$, the canonical answers are Fano's
inequality (Fano, 1961), in the sharp binary form
$H(f \mid \Pi) \le H_{\mathrm{bin}}(\varepsilon^{*}_{\Pi})$, and
the HellmanŌĆōRaviv upper bound (Hellman & Raviv, 1970),
$\varepsilon^{*}_{\Pi} \le \tfrac{1}{2}H(f \mid \Pi)$. The two-sided
packaging is attributed to Feder & Merhav (1994), whose
concave-envelope construction identifies the convex hull of
admissible (entropy, error) pairs over all binary $f$ and all side
channels.

The present note collects this material in the one form most
useful for downstream applications ŌĆö a closed-form two-sided
bracket for a finite *partition* (rather than a general channel)
of a finite set ŌĆö and contributes three small refinements.

**Contributions.**

a. A self-contained statement and proof of the bracket
   (Theorem 1) for finite partitions and binary tasks, using only
   finite sums and elementary concavity.
b. A unification of the two halves as opposite Jaynes
   maximum-entropy programs (┬¦4), making explicit the primal/dual
   correspondence between the FederŌĆōMerhav concave-envelope
   construction and the Lagrangian calculation in the style of
   Massey (1994).
c. A negative sharpness result (Proposition 5) ruling out *any*
   closed-form improvement: neither the constant $1/2$ on the
   upper side nor the function $H_{\mathrm{bin}}^{-1}$ on the
   lower side admits a uniform pointwise improvement.

Explicit boundary witnesses (┬¦8) realise both edges of the
achievable region and confirm sharpness.

**Scope.** Every statement is for finite $V$, finite partition
$\Pi$, and binary $f$. We do not pursue multi-class extensions
($|\mathcal{Y}| > 2$), which proceed via the concave-envelope
construction of Feder & Merhav (1994); nor do we pursue
continuous-alphabet generalisations, which require additional
regularity. Applications to expressivity of constant-on-leaves
predictors ŌĆö decision trees, vector quantisers, clustering
classifiers, and depth-$L$ permutation-invariant message-passing
on graphs ŌĆö are sketched in ┬¦9 and deferred to companion work.

---

## 2. Setup

Let $V$ be a finite set with $|V| = n \ge 1$, and let $\Pi$ be a
finite partition of $V$ into nonempty cells
$\Pi = \{C_1, \ldots, C_m\}$. Let $f : V \to \{0, 1\}$ be a
binary label. Endow $V$ with the uniform probability measure
$q_v = 1/n$; the extension to non-uniform weighting is discussed
in the remark below.

**Cell statistics.**

$$
q_C := |C|/n, \qquad
P_C := |C|^{-1} \sum_{v \in C} f(v), \qquad
e_C := \min(P_C,\, 1 - P_C) \in [0, 1/2].
$$

Thus $q_C$ is the mass of cell $C$, $P_C$ is the cell-conditional
mean of $f$, and $e_C$ is the cell-conditional Bayes error of $f$.

**Partition-conditional entropy.** The partition-conditional
entropy of $f$ given $\Pi$ (in bits) is

$$
H(f \mid \Pi)
:= \sum_{C \in \Pi} q_C \cdot H_{\mathrm{bin}}(P_C)
\;=\; \sum_{C \in \Pi} q_C \cdot H_{\mathrm{bin}}(e_C),
$$

where $H_{\mathrm{bin}}(p) := -p \log_2 p - (1-p) \log_2(1-p)$ with
the convention $0 \log_2 0 := 0$, and the second equality is the
symmetry $H_{\mathrm{bin}}(p) = H_{\mathrm{bin}}(1-p)$.

**Partition Bayes error.** The minimum error of any predictor
constant on each cell of $\Pi$ is

$$
\varepsilon^{*}_{\Pi}
:= \min_{g : \Pi \to \{0, 1\}}
   \Pr\bigl[g(C(v)) \neq f(v)\bigr]
\;=\; \sum_{C \in \Pi} q_C \cdot e_C, \tag{2.1}
$$

attained by the plug-in rule
$\hat{h}_\Pi(v) := \mathbf{1}\{P_{C(v)} \ge 1/2\}$, where $C(v)$
is the cell containing $v$. Equivalently, $\varepsilon^{*}_{\Pi}$
is the Bayes risk of $f$ when the predictor is restricted to
depend on $v$ only through $C(v)$ (Devroye, Gy├Črfi & Lugosi 1996,
┬¦2.1).

**Inverse binary entropy.** The function
$H_{\mathrm{bin}} : [0,1] \to [0,1]$ is strictly concave with
maximum $H_{\mathrm{bin}}(1/2) = 1$ and is strictly increasing on
$[0, 1/2]$. Its inverse on the increasing branch is the unique
function $H_{\mathrm{bin}}^{-1} : [0,1] \to [0, 1/2]$ satisfying
$H_{\mathrm{bin}}(H_{\mathrm{bin}}^{-1}(h)) = h$ for all $h \in [0,1]$.
It is continuous, concave, and strictly increasing.

> **Remark (non-uniform weighting).** Replacing the uniform
> measure $q_v = 1/n$ by any probability mass
> $\{q_v\}_{v\in V}$ with $\sum_v q_v = 1$, and redefining
> $q_C := \sum_{v\in C} q_v$ and
> $P_C := q_C^{-1} \sum_{v\in C} q_v f(v)$, leaves every statement
> and proof in ┬¦┬¦3, 5, 8 unchanged: the only properties of
> $\{q_C\}$ used are nonnegativity and $\sum_C q_C = 1$.

---

## 3. Main result

**Theorem 1** (Two-sided sandwich). *For every finite partition
$\Pi$ of a finite set $V$ and every binary label $f : V \to \{0,1\}$,*

$$
H_{\mathrm{bin}}^{-1}\!\bigl(H(f \mid \Pi)\bigr)
\;\le\; \varepsilon^{*}_{\Pi}
\;\le\; \tfrac{1}{2}\,H(f \mid \Pi). \tag{3.1}
$$

Both bounds are classical. The lower bound is Fano's inequality
(Fano, 1961) in its sharp binary form (Cover & Thomas 2006,
Thm 2.10.1); the upper bound is Hellman & Raviv (1970); the
two-sided packaging is Feder & Merhav (1994, Thm 1). The
contribution of ┬¦┬¦4ŌĆō5 is to present both halves as the optimal
values of a single pair of Jaynes maximum-entropy programs (Jaynes
1957), in the compact derivation style of Massey (1994).

**Achievable region.** Combining the two halves, every pair
$(\varepsilon, H) = (\varepsilon^{*}_{\Pi}, H(f\mid\Pi))$ arising
from a finite partition of a finite set and a binary label lies
in the closed region

$$
\widetilde{A}_2
:= \bigl\{\,(\varepsilon, H) \in [0, 1/2] \times [0, 1]
   \;:\; H_{\mathrm{bin}}^{-1}(H) \le \varepsilon \le H/2 \,\bigr\}.
$$

The two boundaries of $\widetilde A_2$ are realised by explicit
one-parameter families (┬¦8); hence $\widetilde A_2$ is exactly the
closure of achievable pairs.

**Quantified slack.** The width of the sandwich,

$$
w(H) := \tfrac{1}{2}H - H_{\mathrm{bin}}^{-1}(H),
$$

vanishes at the endpoints $H \in \{0, 1\}$ and attains its maximum
at the interior critical point $H^{*}$ solving
$H'_{\mathrm{bin}}(H_{\mathrm{bin}}^{-1}(H^{*})) = 2$, i.e. at
$\varepsilon^{*} := H_{\mathrm{bin}}^{-1}(H^{*}) = 1/5$ (since
$\log_2((1-\varepsilon)/\varepsilon) = 2$ gives $\varepsilon = 1/5$).
The maximal slack is therefore

$$
w^{*} = \tfrac{1}{2}H_{\mathrm{bin}}(1/5) - 1/5 \approx 0.1610,
$$

so (3.1) pins $\varepsilon^{*}_{\Pi}$ to a window of width at most
$\approx 0.161$ uniformly in $\Pi$ and $f$.

---

## 4. The Lagrangian view

The two halves of (3.1) are the optimal values of a pair of
opposite Jaynes maximum-entropy programs on the cell statistics
$\{(q_C, e_C)\}_{C \in \Pi}$, viewed as a probability distribution
on $[0, 1/2]$ paired with a constraint.

Fix $\varepsilon \in [0, 1/2]$ and $H \in [0, 1]$. Consider the
two optimisation problems

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text{(F)} \quad
& \sup_{\{(q_C, e_C)\}_C} \sum_C q_C\, H_{\mathrm{bin}}(e_C)
  \quad\text{s.t.}\quad q_C \ge 0,\;\sum_C q_C = 1,\;
  \sum_C q_C\, e_C = \varepsilon, \\
\text{(HR)} \quad
& \sup_{\{(q_C, e_C)\}_C} \sum_C q_C\, e_C
  \quad\text{s.t.}\quad q_C \ge 0,\;\sum_C q_C = 1,\;
  \sum_C q_C\, H_{\mathrm{bin}}(e_C) = H,
\end{aligned}
$$

where the supremum is over all finite collections of pairs
$\{(q_C, e_C)\}$ with $e_C \in [0, 1/2]$.

**Lemma 2** (Lagrangian envelopes). *The optimal value of* (F)
*is* $H_{\mathrm{bin}}(\varepsilon)$, *attained at the constant
interior point* $e_C \equiv \varepsilon$ *(any $q$-mass
distribution). The optimal value of* (HR) *is* $H/2$, *attained at
a two-mass boundary distribution*
$\{e_{C_0}, e_{C_1}\} = \{0, 1/2\}$ *with* $q_{C_1} = H$.

*Proof.* For (F),
$\sum_C q_C H_{\mathrm{bin}}(e_C) \le H_{\mathrm{bin}}(\sum_C q_C e_C) = H_{\mathrm{bin}}(\varepsilon)$
by Jensen's inequality and concavity of $H_{\mathrm{bin}}$ on
$[0, 1]$, with equality when all $e_C$ coincide. For (HR), the
scalar inequality $e \le \tfrac{1}{2} H_{\mathrm{bin}}(e)$ on
$[0, 1/2]$ (Lemma 3 below) gives
$\sum_C q_C e_C \le \tfrac{1}{2} \sum_C q_C H_{\mathrm{bin}}(e_C) = H/2$,
with equality iff each $e_C$ saturates the scalar inequality,
i.e. each $e_C \in \{0, 1/2\}$; the constraint
$\sum_C q_C H_{\mathrm{bin}}(e_C) = H$ then forces $q_{C_1} = H$
on cells with $e_C = 1/2$. Ō¢Ī

Lemma 2 is the entire content of Theorem 1: program (F) certifies
the lower bound after inversion of $H_{\mathrm{bin}}$; program
(HR) is the upper bound directly. The FederŌĆōMerhav primal
concave-envelope construction (Feder & Merhav, 1994) traces the
upper boundary of the achievable region $\widetilde A_2$ by
exactly this two-mass mixture; the Lagrangian dual gives the
closed-form optimal value in one line.

---

## 5. Proof of Theorem 1

We give the elementary, finite-sum proof. Both halves rest on the
following scalar inequality.

**Lemma 3** (Scalar HellmanŌĆōRaviv). *For every $p \in [0, 1]$,*

$$
\min(p,\, 1 - p) \;\le\; \tfrac{1}{2}\, H_{\mathrm{bin}}(p), \tag{5.1}
$$

*with equality iff $p \in \{0, 1/2, 1\}$.*

*Proof.* By the symmetry $p \mapsto 1 - p$ of both sides we may
assume $p \in [0, 1/2]$, so $\min(p, 1-p) = p$ and (5.1) becomes
$g(p) := \tfrac{1}{2} H_{\mathrm{bin}}(p) - p \ge 0$. We have
$g(0) = 0$ and $g(1/2) = 0$. Differentiating,
$g'(p) = \tfrac{1}{2}\log_2((1-p)/p) - 1$, which vanishes at
$p^{*} = 1/5$ and is positive on $[0, 1/5)$, negative on
$(1/5, 1/2]$; hence $g$ is unimodal on $[0, 1/2]$ with
$g(p^{*}) = w^{*} > 0$. In particular $g \ge 0$ on $[0, 1/2]$,
with equality only at the endpoints. Ō¢Ī

*Proof of Theorem 1.*

*Upper bound.* Applying (5.1) with $p = P_C$ to each cell $C$ and
multiplying by $q_C \ge 0$,

$$
q_C \cdot e_C
= q_C \cdot \min(P_C, 1 - P_C)
\le \tfrac{1}{2}\, q_C \cdot H_{\mathrm{bin}}(P_C).
$$

Summing over $C \in \Pi$ and recalling
$\varepsilon^{*}_{\Pi} = \sum_C q_C e_C$ and
$H(f \mid \Pi) = \sum_C q_C H_{\mathrm{bin}}(P_C)$ gives
$\varepsilon^{*}_{\Pi} \le \tfrac{1}{2} H(f \mid \Pi)$.

*Lower bound.* The symmetry $H_{\mathrm{bin}}(P_C) = H_{\mathrm{bin}}(e_C)$
yields

$$
H(f \mid \Pi) = \sum_C q_C\, H_{\mathrm{bin}}(e_C). \tag{5.2}
$$

The function $H_{\mathrm{bin}}$ is concave on $[0,1]$, hence on
$[0, 1/2]$. Jensen's inequality with weights $\{q_C\}_C$ (which
sum to one) applied to $\{e_C\}_C \subset [0, 1/2]$ gives

$$
\sum_C q_C\, H_{\mathrm{bin}}(e_C)
\le H_{\mathrm{bin}}\!\Bigl(\sum_C q_C\, e_C\Bigr)
= H_{\mathrm{bin}}(\varepsilon^{*}_{\Pi}). \tag{5.3}
$$

Combining (5.2)ŌĆō(5.3), $H(f \mid \Pi) \le H_{\mathrm{bin}}(\varepsilon^{*}_{\Pi})$.
Since $\varepsilon^{*}_{\Pi} \in [0, 1/2]$ and $H_{\mathrm{bin}}^{-1}$
is the inverse of $H_{\mathrm{bin}}$ on the increasing branch
$[0, 1/2]$, applying $H_{\mathrm{bin}}^{-1}$ to both sides yields
$H_{\mathrm{bin}}^{-1}(H(f \mid \Pi)) \le \varepsilon^{*}_{\Pi}$. Ō¢Ī

> **Remark (Gini shadow of the upper bound).** A useful corollary
> of (5.1) is the variance inequality
> $\varepsilon^{*}_{\Pi} \le 2\, \mathbb{E}[\mathrm{Var}(f \mid \Pi)] = 2 \sum_C q_C P_C (1 - P_C)$,
> the cell-wise GiniŌĆōBayes inequality (Breiman et al., 1984).
> When all $P_C \in \mathbb{Q}$, the variance form is rational and
> admits exact arithmetic, which is convenient for mechanised
> verification.

---

## 6. Refinement monotonicity

A partition $\Pi'$ *refines* $\Pi$, written $\Pi' \preceq \Pi$,
if every cell of $\Pi'$ is contained in some cell of $\Pi$.

**Proposition 4** (Refinement monotonicity). *If
$\Pi' \preceq \Pi$, then for every binary $f : V \to \{0, 1\}$,*

$$
H(f \mid \Pi') \le H(f \mid \Pi),
\qquad
\varepsilon^{*}_{\Pi'} \le \varepsilon^{*}_{\Pi}.
$$

*Proof.* Fix $C \in \Pi$ and write $C = \bigsqcup_j C'_j$ as the
disjoint union of its sub-cells in $\Pi'$, with masses $q_{C'_j}$
satisfying $\sum_j q_{C'_j} = q_C$. The cell mean
$P_C = q_C^{-1} \sum_j q_{C'_j} P_{C'_j}$ is a convex combination
of $\{P_{C'_j}\}_j$ with weights $q_{C'_j}/q_C$. Concavity of
$H_{\mathrm{bin}}$ on $[0, 1]$ gives
$q_C^{-1} \sum_j q_{C'_j} H_{\mathrm{bin}}(P_{C'_j}) \le H_{\mathrm{bin}}(P_C)$,
hence
$\sum_j q_{C'_j} H_{\mathrm{bin}}(P_{C'_j}) \le q_C H_{\mathrm{bin}}(P_C)$.
Summing over $C \in \Pi$ gives the entropy claim. The error claim
follows by the same argument applied to the concave function
$p \mapsto \min(p, 1-p)$ on $[0,1]$. Ō¢Ī

This is the deterministic-coarsening case of the data-processing
inequality (Cover & Thomas, 2006, Thm 2.8.1). We record the
elementary proof to keep this note self-contained.

---

## 7. Sharpness

We now show that no closed-form improvement of either bound is
possible.

**Proposition 5** (Unimprovability).

(i) *For every constant $c < 1/2$ there exists a finite partition
$\Pi$ of a finite $V$ and a binary $f$ with
$\varepsilon^{*}_{\Pi} > c \cdot H(f \mid \Pi)$. In particular, no
constant smaller than $1/2$ can replace the coefficient on the
right-hand side of (3.1).*

(ii) *For every continuous function $\psi : [0, 1] \to [0, 1/2]$
with $\psi(H_0) > H_{\mathrm{bin}}^{-1}(H_0)$ at some
$H_0 \in (0, 1)$, there exists a finite partition $\Pi$ of a
finite $V$ and a binary $f$ with $\varepsilon^{*}_{\Pi} < \psi(H(f \mid \Pi))$.
In particular, $H_{\mathrm{bin}}^{-1}$ cannot be replaced on the
left-hand side of (3.1) by any pointwise-larger continuous
function.*

*Proof.*
(i) The upper-boundary family $\Pi^{\mathrm{HR}}_\alpha$
constructed in ┬¦8 achieves equality
$\varepsilon^{*}_{\Pi} = \tfrac{1}{2} H(f \mid \Pi)$ for every
$\alpha \in (0, 1]$, hence for every $c < 1/2$ any such row
witnesses $\varepsilon^{*}_{\Pi} > c \cdot H(f \mid \Pi)$.

(ii) Set $\delta := \psi(H_0) - H_{\mathrm{bin}}^{-1}(H_0) > 0$.
By continuity of $\psi$ and of $H_{\mathrm{bin}}^{-1}$, there is
an open neighbourhood $U \ni H_0$ in $(0, 1)$ on which
$\psi(H) > H_{\mathrm{bin}}^{-1}(H) + \delta/2$. Pick a rational
$\varepsilon \in (0, 1/2)$ with $H_{\mathrm{bin}}(\varepsilon) \in U$,
and let $n$ be a positive integer with $\varepsilon n \in \mathbb{Z}$.
The lower-boundary family $\Pi^{\mathrm{F}}_\varepsilon$ of ┬¦8 on
this $n$ satisfies $\varepsilon^{*}_{\Pi} = \varepsilon$ and
$H(f \mid \Pi) = H_{\mathrm{bin}}(\varepsilon) \in U$, hence
$\varepsilon^{*}_{\Pi} = H_{\mathrm{bin}}^{-1}(H(f \mid \Pi)) < \psi(H(f \mid \Pi))$. Ō¢Ī

The rhetorical content of Proposition 5 is in the style of Massey
(1994, ┬¦III): a positive sharpness claim upgraded to a negative
non-existence claim. Theorem 1 together with Proposition 5
identifies $\widetilde A_2$ as the tightest two-sided closed-form
bracket on $(\varepsilon^{*}_{\Pi}, H(f \mid \Pi))$ available in
the binary case.

> **Remark (multi-class).** For label alphabets of size $M > 2$
> the sharp bracket replaces $H_{\mathrm{bin}}^{-1}$ by the lower
> concave envelope of admissible (entropy, error) pairs on
> $\{1, \ldots, M\}$; this is the construction of Feder & Merhav
> (1994). A multi-class strengthening of the HellmanŌĆōRaviv upper
> bound via $f$-divergences is given by Hashlamoun, Varshney &
> Samarasooriya (1994); specialised to $M = 2$ their bound
> coincides with (5.1).

---

## 8. Tightness

Both boundaries of $\widetilde A_2$ are realised by explicit
one-parameter families on a finite $V = \{1, \ldots, n\}$ under
uniform weighting.

**Lower (Fano) boundary $\Pi^{\mathrm{F}}_\varepsilon$.** Fix
$\varepsilon \in [0, 1/2]$ and $n$ with $\varepsilon n \in \mathbb{Z}$.
Take the trivial partition $\Pi^{\mathrm{F}}_\varepsilon := \{V\}$
and let $f$ have exactly $\varepsilon n$ ones. Then
$P_C = e_C = \varepsilon$,

$$
H(f \mid \Pi^{\mathrm{F}}_\varepsilon) = H_{\mathrm{bin}}(\varepsilon),
\qquad
\varepsilon^{*}_{\Pi^{\mathrm{F}}_\varepsilon} = \varepsilon,
$$

attaining the lower bound of (3.1) with equality and tracing the
curve $\varepsilon = H_{\mathrm{bin}}^{-1}(H)$ as $\varepsilon$
varies over $[0, 1/2]$.

**Upper (HellmanŌĆōRaviv) boundary $\Pi^{\mathrm{HR}}_\alpha$.** Fix
$\alpha \in [0, 1]$ and $n$ with $\alpha n \in 2\mathbb{Z}$.
Partition $V = C_0 \sqcup C_1$ with $|C_1| = \alpha n$,
$|C_0| = (1 - \alpha) n$, set $f \equiv 0$ on $C_0$, and let $f$
be exactly half-zero / half-one on $C_1$. Then $e_{C_0} = 0$,
$e_{C_1} = 1/2$, $q_{C_0} = 1 - \alpha$, $q_{C_1} = \alpha$, so

$$
H(f \mid \Pi^{\mathrm{HR}}_\alpha) = \alpha,
\qquad
\varepsilon^{*}_{\Pi^{\mathrm{HR}}_\alpha}
= \alpha / 2
= \tfrac{1}{2}\, H(f \mid \Pi^{\mathrm{HR}}_\alpha),
$$

attaining the upper bound of (3.1) with equality and tracing the
line $\varepsilon = H/2$ as $\alpha$ varies over $[0, 1]$.

The balanced limit $\alpha = 1$ collapses the sandwich at
$H = 1$, $\varepsilon = 1/2$,
$H_{\mathrm{bin}}^{-1}(1) = 1/2 = \tfrac{1}{2}\cdot 1$. The pure
limit $\alpha = 0$ collapses the sandwich at $H = 0$,
$\varepsilon = 0$.

**Tightness of the slack.** The maximal slack
$w^{*} \approx 0.1610$ is attained on the lower boundary at
$\varepsilon = 1/5$: the Fano witness $\Pi^{\mathrm{F}}_{1/5}$ on
any $n$ divisible by $5$ realises
$(\varepsilon, H, w(H)) = (1/5,\, H_{\mathrm{bin}}(1/5),\, w^{*})$.

---

## 9. Discussion and applications

Theorem 1 is a uniform two-sided bracket on the Bayes error of
any predictor constrained to be constant on the cells of a fixed
partition. Three immediate application domains follow this shape.

**Decision trees.** Each leaf of a finite decision tree
corresponds to a cell, and a leaf-constant predictor is a
constant-on-cells predictor in the sense of (2.1). Theorem 1
therefore brackets the training-set Bayes risk of any such tree
by its label entropy conditioned on the leaf partition,
two-sidedly, with the quantified slack of ┬¦3.

**Vector quantisation and clustering.** A $k$-codeword vector
quantiser, or a hard clustering produced by $k$-means or spectral
clustering, induces a finite partition of its input set. The
bracket bounds the supervised classification error of any
classifier constrained to be constant on codewords (equivalently,
of nearest-codeword classification) in terms of the
post-quantisation label entropy.

**Permutation-invariant message passing.** A depth-$L$
permutation-invariant message-passing predictor on a finite graph
$G$ is constant on the cells of the WeisfeilerŌĆōLeman colour
refinement at depth $L$, by an elementary induction on layers.
Theorem 1 therefore brackets the error of every such predictor by
the partition-conditional entropy of the task given the depth-$L$
refinement. This application is the motivating one for the
present note; we develop it elsewhere.

**What is genuinely new.** The two inequalities themselves are
not new. What is new is (a) the explicit Jaynes-Lagrangian
unification of ┬¦4 and Lemma 2, which gives both halves as
opposite max-entropy programs on the same variables and makes
explicit a primal/dual correspondence between the FederŌĆōMerhav
concave-envelope construction and the Massey-style Lagrangian
derivation; (b) the negative sharpness result Proposition 5,
which establishes that the bracket is unimprovable in closed
form; and (c) the quantified-slack bound $w^{*} \approx 0.161$
uniform in $\Pi$ and $f$.

---

## 10. Related work

The upper bound (5.1) is Hellman & Raviv (1970, eq. 6); an
earlier appearance of a related entropy upper bound on Bayes
error is Tebbe & Dwyer (1968) and Kovalevsky (1968). The lower
bound is Fano's inequality (Fano, 1961) in the binary form of
Cover & Thomas (2006, Thm 2.10.1). The two-sided achievable-region
packaging is Feder & Merhav (1994, Thm 1); Santhi & Vardy (2006)
give a further improvement on the lower bound under a different
optimisation. The Lagrangian / maximum-entropy view appears in
Jaynes (1957) and in the guessing-entropy work of Massey (1994);
the contribution here is to make the primal/dual correspondence
between the two classical packagings explicit. Prior-aware
sharpenings of the Fano half via data processing on the binary
error indicator (e.g. Han & Verd├║, 1994) are available when the
label marginal is bounded away from $1/2$; they are orthogonal to
the closed-form bracket studied here and are pursued elsewhere.

---

## 11. Conclusion

We have given a self-contained two-sided closed-form bracket on
the Bayes error of any constant-on-cells predictor for any finite
partition of a finite set and any binary label, with proof, sharp
boundary witnesses, a uniform slack bound of $\approx 0.161$, a
unimprovability statement, and a forward pointer to a prior-aware
sharpening. All arguments are elementary, use only finite sums,
and are amenable to mechanisation in proof assistants such as
Lean 4 or Isabelle/HOL.

---

